To set up a DHCP server on Red Hat Enterprise Linux, you will need to install the `kea` package and configure it.

Here are the general steps:

1.  **Install the DHCP server package:**

    ```bash
    # dnf install kea
    ```

2.  **Configure the DHCPv4 server:**

    The configuration involves creating a `kea-dhcp4.conf` file, typically located in `/etc/kea/`. This file will define your subnets, IP address ranges, DNS servers, and other DHCP options.

    For example, a basic configuration might look like this:

    ```json
    {
    "Dhcp4": {
        "interfaces": [ { "interface": "enp1s0" } ],
        "lease-database": {
            "type": "memfile",
            "persist": true,
            "name": "dhcp4-leases.csv",
            "lfc-interval": 3600
        },
        "control-socket": {
            "socket-type": "unix",
            "socket-name": "/tmp/kea4-ctrl-socket"
        },
        "config-backends": [
            {
                "type": "json",
                "connections": [
                    {
                        "uri": "/etc/kea/kea-dhcp4.conf"
                    }
                ]
            }
        ],
        "loggers": [
            {
                "name": "kea-dhcp4",
                "output_options": [
                    {
                        "output": "stdout",
                        "pattern": "%d %-5p %m\n"
                    }
                ],
                "severity": "INFO"
            }
        ],
        "subnet4": [
            {
                "subnet": "192.168.124.0/24",
                "pools": [ { "pool": "192.168.124.10-192.168.124.200" } ],
                "option-data": [
                    {
                        "name": "routers",
                        "data": "192.168.124.1"
                    },
                    {
                        "name": "domain-name-servers",
                        "data": "192.168.124.1"
                    }
                ]
            }
        ]
    }
    }
    ```

    Remember to replace `enp1s0`, `192.168.124.0/24`, `192.168.124.10-192.168.124.200`, and `192.168.124.1` with your network interface, network address, IP pool range, and DNS/router IP address, respectively.

3.  **Enable and start the `kea-dhcp4` service:**

    ```bash
    # systemctl enable kea-dhcp4
    # systemctl start kea-dhcp4
    ```

For detailed configuration options and advanced setups, including DHCPv6 and network boot environments, you should consult the official Red Hat documentation.

**Sources:**
- [Red Hat Enterprise Linux Life Cycle](https://access.redhat.com/support/policy/updates/errata)
- [title](https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en-us/red_hat_enterprise_linux/10/html-single/automatically_installing_rhel/index)

